The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Authentication In K8s

Kubernetes authentication ensures that the identity of the users and their access to the cluster resources are properly managed.

In this example, we will create authentication for a student user within the devops namespace.

Open New Terminal (Optional)

If current working directory is not workspace/course

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as workspace/course
cd course/

Demo:

  • Create a new folder and change the directory to perform the lab.
mkdir 3.9_authz_authn && cd 3.9_authz_authn
  • Generate a private key for the student, this command generates a 2048-bit RSA private key for the student user.

openssl genrsa -out student.key 2048
  • Create a Certificate Signing Request (CSR), this command creates a CSR using the student's private key. The CSR will be used to request a signed certificate from the Kubernetes cluster.
openssl req -new -key student.key -out student.csr -subj "/CN=student/O=devops"

  • Base64 encode the CSR, the CSR is Base64 encoded, which is required for the next step in creating a CertificateSigningRequest resource.
student_b64_encoded=$(cat student.csr | base64 | tr -d '\n')
sudo bash -c "cat << EOF > signing-request.yaml
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: student.csr
spec:
  groups:
  - system:authenticated
  request: ${student_b64_encoded}
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  usages:
  - client auth
EOF"

A YAML file is created with the necessary information for Kubernetes to process the CSR.

  • Apply the CertificateSigningRequest YAML file, this command submits the CSR to the Kubernetes cluster.
kubectl create -f signing-request.yaml

  • Check the status of the CSR, this command lists the CertificateSigningRequests, allowing you to check the status of the student's CSR.
kubectl get csr

  • Approve the CSR, (the cluster administrator approves the CSR, which allows the certificate to be issued.)
kubectl certificate approve student.csr

  • Retrieve the signed certificate, this command retrieves the signed certificate from the approved CSR and saves it to the student.crt file.
kubectl get csr student.csr -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' | base64 --decode > student.crt

  • Set the student's credentials in the kubeconfig, this command adds the student's credentials, including the signed certificate and private key, to the kubeconfig file.
kubectl config set-credentials student --client-certificate=student.crt --client-key=student.key

  • Create the devops namespace.
kubectl create namespace devops

  • Check the student's access to the devops namespace.
kubectl auth can-i list pods --namespace devops --as student

The output shows "no" because the student user has been authenticated but not yet authorized for any specific actions within the devops namespace. Authorization needs to be granted separately through role-based access control (RBAC) policies.
